<n-docbody><doc bill="Y"><content.metadata.block><cmd.identifiers><cmd.cites><cmd.second.line.cite><bop/><bos/>Multidistrict Lit Man § 11:4<eos/><eop/></cmd.second.line.cite></cmd.cites></cmd.identifiers></content.metadata.block><prop.block><prop.head toc-guid=""><bop/><bos/><headtext>Multidistrict Litigation Manual</headtext><eos/><eop/></prop.head><content.metadata.block><cmd.dates><cmd.currency.default iso.d="20190501"><bop/><bos/>May 2019 Update<eos/><eop/></cmd.currency.default></cmd.dates></content.metadata.block><author.line><bop/><bos/><author>David F. Herr[<footnote.reference refid="If6a120d16b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2">a0</footnote.reference>]</author><eos/><eop/></author.line><prop.head toc-guid="I97b7f560933b11da99e2b07024dacc26"><bop/><bos/><label.name>Part</label.name><label.designator>I.</label.designator><headtext>Handling Cases Before the Judicial Panel on Multidistrict Litigation</headtext><eos/><eop/></prop.head><prop.head toc-guid="I6a719380933c11da99e2b07024dacc26"><bop/><bos/><label.name>Chapter</label.name><label.designator>11.</label.designator><headtext>Appeal</headtext><eos/><eop/></prop.head></prop.block><message.block><include.copyright n-include_collection="w_wlnv_msg" n-include_guid="I1DA35ED81DD211B281BAD200220BDFCA">Copyright (c) 2017 Thomson/RIA All rights reserved.</include.copyright></message.block><section><section.front><doc.title toc-guid="I94fa2c36e1e311da9c26e67ca3b71335"><head parent="doc.title"><bop/><bos/><label.name>§ </label.name><label.designator>11:4.</label.designator><headtext>Review by the Panel of transferee court decisions—The long answer</headtext><eos/><eop/></head></doc.title></section.front><section.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>It doesn&apos;t review transferee court decisions. <eos/><bos/>The Panel has also been careful to insure that it does not permit the parties to “end-run” the Panel&apos;s reluctance to review transferee court decisions by seeking retransfer or remand. <eos/><bos/>In one case the Panel considered a motion to retransfer based upon fears about the transferee judge&apos;s rulings and the possibility that he might transfer the cases to himself for trial. <eos/><bos/>The Panel concluded: <begin.quote ID="QT_0001"/>“Section 1407 does not authorize the Panel to act as an appellate forum for every litigant disgruntled by the rulings of a transferee judge.”<eos/><bos/><end.quote refid="QT_0001"/>[<footnote.reference refid="If6a120d26b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2">1</footnote.reference>]</paratext><eos/><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>The circuit court having jurisdiction over appeals taken from the transferor court has no jurisdiction over appeals in the action after transfer has been ordered.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="If6a147e06b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2">2</footnote.reference>]</paratext><eos/><eop/></para></section.body></section><author.footnotes><footnote ID="If6a120d16b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2"><label.designator>a0</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>Maslon Edelman Borman &amp; Brand, LLP, Minneapolis, Minnesota.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote></author.footnotes><footnote.block><footnote ID="If6a120d26b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2"><label.designator>1</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0304914150" w-serial-number="1971106847" w-seq-number="00001" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000345" w-pinpoint-page="1048" ID="I74c51c116b3e11e99434cc59995e5150">In re Plumbing Fixtures, 332 F. Supp. 1047, 1048 (J.P.M.L. 1971)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="If6a147e06b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2"><label.designator>2</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0304914150" w-serial-number="1987121256" w-seq-number="00002" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000350" ID="I74c591416b3e11e99434cc59995e5150">FMC Corp. v. Glouster Engineering Co., 830 F.2d 770 (7th Cir. 1987)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote></footnote.block><content.metadata.block><cmd.royalty><cmd.copyright><bop/><bos/>Westlaw. © 2019 Thomson Reuters.  <eos/><bos/>No Claim to Orig. U.S. Govt. <eos/><bos/>Works.<eos/><eop/></cmd.copyright></cmd.royalty><cmd.identifiers><cmd.cites><cmd.first.line.cite><bop/><bos/>MDLITMAN § 11:4<eos/><eop/></cmd.first.line.cite></cmd.cites></cmd.identifiers></content.metadata.block></doc></n-docbody>
